  "text": "Salmonella fepB ferric iron transporter mutants colonize mice poorly in competitive infections. We constructed a mutant Salmonella Typhimurium SL1344 strain with a deletion of fepB, encoding a protein crucial for ferric iron uptake. To establish whether FepB is needed for Salmonella survival and growth in tissue, mixed-infection experiments were performed in Sv129S6 (Nramp1 ϩ/ϩ ) mice. These mice become chronically infected with Salmonella and can be used to monitor infection long term [CITATION_1] . We evaluated the number of wild-type organisms and the number of fepB mutant organisms in feces, a close proxy for the number of organisms in the cecum (39), at 1 and 3 days postinfection. At 1 day postinfection, equivalent numbers of wild-type and ⌬fepB mutant bacteria were recovered from fecal pellets, indicating that the ⌬fepB mutant colonizes the intestine well initially (Fig. 1A) . However, by 3 days postinfection, the ⌬fepB mutant had 100-to 10,000-fold-decreased colonization relative to the wild-type organism (Fig. 1A) .",
